"McCarroll D.","Future climate change and the British Quaternary research community",2010,"Quaternary Science Reviews","29","13-14",,"1661","1672",,,10.1016/j.quascirev.2010.04.003,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77954819207&partnerID=40&md5=1684f9820f943c54a917b3d7528092f5","Department of Geography, Swansea University, SA2 8PP Wales, United Kingdom","McCarroll, D., Department of Geography, Swansea University, SA2 8PP Wales, United Kingdom","The uncertainty surrounding estimates of future global warming, even given a single scenario for increasing greenhouse gas emissions, is unacceptably large and has not declined substantially over the last three decades. The Quaternary science community is uniquely placed to constrain the array of possible futures by providing reconstructions of past climate that can be used, together with instrumental data, to weight the model variants in perturbed physics ensembles, which accept the uncertainty in many of the model parameters. The models which give the best fit with the climate of the past can then be given most weight when projected into the future. Computing resources have restricted such experiments to relatively simple models, so that information on spatial differences in palaeoclimate could not be fully exploited. Within a few years it will be possible to apply this method to complex general circulation models, so if the Quaternary community acts now it will be possible to supply the information that is required. The best time period to use is the last one to two thousand years. The wider the range of climate parameters that can be reconstructed, and the wider the range of locations, the more constraint will be provided. To be useful, the palaeoclimate reconstructions need to have realistic estimates of uncertainty, so a clear emphasis on replication, calibration and verification will be required. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd.",,"Best fit; Calibration and verification; Climate parameters; Complex general circulation models; Computing resource; Future climate; Instrumental data; Model parameters; Palaeoclimate; Palaeoclimate reconstruction; Possible futures; Quaternary science; Research communities; Simple model; Spatial differences; Time periods; Earth atmosphere; Gas emissions; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Uncertainty analysis; Climate models; climate prediction; emission inventory; ensemble forecasting; future prospect; general circulation model; global warming; greenhouse gas; paleoclimate; Quaternary; reconstruction; uncertainty analysis",,,,,,"Alley, R.B., Cuffey, K.M., Oxygen- and hydrogen-isotopic ratios of water in precipitation: beyond paleothermometry (2001) Stable Isotope Geochemistry, 43, pp. 527-553; Ambrose, W.G., Carroll, M.L., Greenacre, M., Thorrold, S.R., McMahon, K.W., Variation in Serripes groenlandicus (Bivalvia) growth in a Norwegian high-Arctic fjord: evidence for local- and large-scale climatic forcing (2006) Global Change Biology, 12 (9), pp. 1595-1607; Baker, A., Smart, P.L., Edwards, R.L., Richards, D.A., Annual growth banding in a cave stalagmite (1993) Nature, 364 (6437), pp. 518-520; Ballantyne, C.K., McCarroll, D., Stone, J.O., The Donegal ice dome, northwest Ireland: dimensions and chronology (2007) Journal of Quaternary Science, 22 (8), pp. 773-783; Ballantyne, C.K., Stone, J.O., McCarroll, D., Dimensions and chronology of the last ice sheet in Western Ireland (2008) Quaternary Science Reviews, 27 (3-4), pp. 185-200; Barber, K.E., Chambers, F.M., Maddy, D., Holocene palaeoclimates from peat stratigraphy: macrofossil proxy climate records from three oceanic raised bogs in England and Ireland (2003) Quaternary Science Reviews, 22 (5-7), pp. 521-539; Barber, K., Dumayne-Peaty, L., Hughes, P., Mauquoy, D., Scaife, R., Replicability and variability of the recent macrofossil and proxy-climate record from raised bogs: field stratigraphy and macrofossil data from Bolton Fell Moss and Walton Moss, Cumbria, England (1998) Journal of Quaternary S